\begin_layout Title
Angular Formulation of Conformal Transform and Free Network Constraints
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Start with classic conformal transformation involving three distinct components:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
General translation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Classic angular rotation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Overall scaling dialation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formulate this algebraically as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=\lambda R\left(x-t\right)R^{\dagger}\label{eq:CanonicalConform}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is a vector representing general translation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a spinor representing (square root of) of rotation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is a scalar value representing dilation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formulate this in terms of (generalized) angular quantities via substitutions
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\lambda & = & e^{\rho}\\
R & = & e^{\frac{1}{2}\Phi}\\
t & = & e^{\tau}e^{\frac{1}{2}\Theta}ae^{\frac{1}{2}\Theta^{\dagger}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is scalar representing a post-translation angular dilation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is scalar representing a pre-translation angular dilation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 is bivector representing classic rotation angle associated with change
 in attitude
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta$
\end_inset

 is (restricted) bivector representing translation direction as a rotated
 reference vector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is arbitrary reference vector with respect to which direction angle, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta$
\end_inset

, is reduced
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The restriction on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta$
\end_inset

 in terms of arbitrary fixed direction vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, may be expressed as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2a\wedge\Theta=0
\]

\end_inset

or equivalently, that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 anti-commutes with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\Theta=-\Theta a
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The magnitude of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 provides the reference scale for all other entities.
 I.e.
 assume that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a^{2}\equiv1
\]

\end_inset

which defines the scale of all other relationships.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, in a classic dextral ortho-normal basis, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ e_{k}\right\} $
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $7$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom of the conformal transformation may be expressed in
 polar form (with respect to reference pole, 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

) as,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\rho & = & \rho_{0}1\\
\tau & = & \tau_{0}1\\
\Phi & = & \phi_{1}e_{2}e_{3}+\phi_{2}e_{3}e_{1}+\phi_{3}e_{1}e_{2}\\
\Theta & = & \vartheta_{1}e_{2}e_{3}+\vartheta_{2}e_{3}e_{1}+0\\
a & = & e_{3}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Convert three independent vectors to ortho-norm basis via an orthogonalization
 process such that,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
e_{3} & \equiv & a=\frac{1}{2}\left(a+e_{0}ae_{0}^{-1}\right)\\
e_{1} & \propto & \frac{1}{2}\left(e_{3}-e_{3}be_{3}^{-1}\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(e_{3}-e_{3}be_{3}\right)\\
e_{2} & \propto & \frac{1}{2}\left(c-\left(e_{3}e_{1}c\left(e_{3}e_{1}\right)^{-1}\right)\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(c-\left(e_{3}e_{1}ce_{1}e_{3}\right)\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In terms of the generalized angle parameters, the canonical conformal transforma
tion equation
